english:
  title: Record of a River Journey
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the year of Gicchuuk, on the sixteenth day of the fifth month, I boarded a boat at night from Wonsan near Chinjiang and traveled upriver to Longyeon. Though the sky had not yet brightened, the monk Seonjung and the official Pan were already waiting on the shore. Together we turned northward, and by evening reached the ancient city. The next day we arrived beneath Falling Flower Rock at Buyeo.

    Once, when Tang armies came to conquer the old Baekje, Buyeo was its ancient capital. When the siege grew desperate, the king and nobles fled, abandoning the palace ladies. Those noble women, unwilling to suffer dishonor at enemy hands, gathered at this cliff and threw themselves into the waters. Thus the rock bears its name.

    The local magistrate had prepared a meal for us at a temple by the rock. As afternoon deepened, we cast off and drifted westward. There, a great stone rose from the water, towering and strange. Below lay depths too vast to fathom. When Tang soldiers arrived and camped across the river, fog and clouds obscured their crossing. They say a dragon dwelt beneath, protecting the kingdom. The Tang sorcerers cast bait and drew it forth. The dragon resisted at first, then yielded. The stone was gouged by its struggle—a mark remains, more than a foot deep and wide, stretching perhaps ten feet from water to summit. They call it the Dragon-Fishing Terrace.

    West of this, five li distant on the southern bank, stands a temple called Tiger Rock. The cliff face rises sheer, and upon it are marks like tiger claws ascending. Further west, a precipice drops a thousand feet. Its summit they call Heaven's Council Terrace. In Baekje times, they say, this place touched heaven itself. When officials needed to be appointed, their names were written and left upon the terrace, while the king and courtiers knelt in their robes upon the northern shore, waiting for heaven to mark the chosen names. This is what the locals claim. Now nothing remains but stone suspended in air.

    These are the Four Renowns of Buyeo—celebrated sights that draw those who love grand undertakings across a thousand leagues. My homeland lies scarcely sixty li from here. Since youth I have passed nearby many times, yet never once truly beheld these places. I thought myself a man of modest ambitions. Yet now, in harvest season, I have led a hundred souls with music and dance, provision carts and honored guests, and spent three days in travel. Am I not then a lover of grand undertakings?

    Still, history records nothing of these events. No inscriptions survive to verify them. The tales border on the strange, and who can trust the local accounts? Besides, what we see falls short of what we hear. I write this down as a warning to those seekers who come after me, and as a record of my own folly.
  footnotes:
    - Gicchuuk refers to 己丑 in the sexagenary cycle, corresponding to 1349 CE.
    - 'The ''Four Renowns'' (四詠) of Buyeo are the four legendary sites described: Falling Flower Rock, Dragon-Fishing Terrace, Tiger Rock, and Heaven''s Council Terrace.'
    - Falling Flower Rock commemorates the tragedy of Baekje palace ladies who chose death over capture when Tang armies besieged the kingdom in 660 CE.
